[normal]Written evidence from London Borough of Lambeth
[normal]Lambeth is one of a growing number of councils that ar
[normal]e becoming cooperative
[normal] councils. That means putting people who use our services or live in our communities in control of the decisions that affect their lives. At its core it is about citizens, councillors and council staff working together to determine local outcomes and how best to deliver those. 
[normal]Lambeth
[normal] has developed its own ambitious public service reform programme to become a cooperative council. 
[normal]Empowering and 
[normal]working with citizens (coproduction
[normal]) is
[normal] central to our 
[normal]approach
[normal] and
[normal] it
[normal] is
[normal] changing the way we think about the rol
[normal]e of local government in public service provision
[normal]. 
[normal] 
[normal]In 
[normal]the context
[normal] of reducing public sector spending we are 
[normal]working with
[normal] citizens to meet their needs
[normal]. In Lambeth we are seeking to build on the assets in our communities and to give power and control back to them, so that they can find ways of helping themselves and others
[normal] to
[normal] lead the lives they want to lead. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Cllr Lib Peck[bold]              [bold]              [bold]              [bold]              [bold]Derrick Anderson[bold]Leader Lambeth Council[bold]              [bold]              [bold]              [bold]Chief Executive  [bold]Lambeth Council [bold]~
[normal]What evidence is there that citizen-centred approaches to public service design, delivery and choice of provider can deliver better outcomes—ensuring not only better value for money, but also greater social, economic and environmental value?/ Why pursue citizen-centred approaches to public service design and delivery?
[normal]Our cooperative approach[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Utilising user and community expertise[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Aspire Wellbeing
[normal]Aspire Wellbeing was a day centre 
[normal]run
[normal] by the council. Encouraged
[normal] by our cooperative direction of travel staff establish
[normal]ed
[normal] themselves as a social enterprise - owned by the existing staff group and with the active involvement of service users and the local community.  The centre is 
[normal]now a
[normal] thriving community resource maximising the local benefits it provides. This includes gym
[normal] 
[normal]membership, studio classes, 
[normal]affordable 
[normal]meeting room hire
[normal], 
[normal]the income from which will be 
[normal]re-
[normal]invested in facilities for the community
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Aspire Wellbeing co–produce their services with all stakeholders; customers, volunteers, staff and the local communities.  
[normal]As 
[normal]part of the government’s mutual pathfinder scheme they also help other social enterprise projects follow in their path; sharing their journey and helping others learn from their mistakes and successes.
[normal] 
[normal]Improving and democratising[bold]Cooperative Libraries
[normal]Faced with the same challenges to library provision as the rest of the country we engaged with a wide range of people around each of our nine libraries. We provided detailed financial and service information and worked with the community develop wh
[normal]at a successful library service
[normal] would look
[normal] like. A plan and budget has been set for each library 
[normal]that has been coproduced with 
[normal]the community. This has resulted in Lambeth retaining all of its existing libraries whilst also reducing the necessary costs. Communities have taken on greater responsibility for libraries, and are tailoring the services offered by the libraries to meet the needs of that particular community.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]A wider understanding of the resources available to us[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]c. 
[normal]              
[normal]W
[normal]e believe that the real value of our cooperative approach lies in 
[normal]bringing greater resources to bear on the challenges we face. 
[normal] Local government revenues are a small, and diminishing, proportion of the total resources available in our borough. 
[normal]There is also a wealth of resources in our communities
[normal], among the people who live and work here, 
[normal]who we can work with, enable
[normal],
[normal] and support to achieve our shared outcomes.
[normal] 
[normal] In Lambeth we believe that providing 
[normal]reactive
[normal] services 
[normal]to
[normal] people is neither sustainable nor effective.  
[normal]We focus on the strengths of citizens to achieve good outcomes: c
[normal]oproduction and an asset-based approach enables the council to grow the existing assets and strengths within our communities
[normal], 
[normal]enabling communities to meet their own needs.  
[normal]The Workshop
[normal]The Workshop is an 
[normal]on-going
[normal] project in West Norwood
[normal].  T
[normal]he first phase of the project involved setting up in a vacant shop in the town centre and holding over 540 conversations with residents
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]generating 
[normal]fresh ideas and seeking 
[normal]new 
[normal]ways to overcome obstacles to collaboration.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]The second phase of the project is now underway
[normal],
[normal] establishing a number of ‘mini-lab’ projects which aim to establish a more collaborative, better-networked, self-sufficient community more capable of taking on further community-led cooperative activities. T
[normal]o enable this transition from a ‘serviced community’ to a ‘collaborative community’ a whole system redesign is being tested 
[normal]exploring
[normal] how:
[normal] 1) citizens interact with each other
[normal] 2) spaces and venues ar
[normal]e used
[normal] 3) networks operat
[normal]e and connect with each other
[normal] 
[normal]4) 
[normal]learning is acquired and shared
[normal] 5) funding and inve
[normal]stment is secured and spent
[normal] 6) procedures and processes are 
[normal]navigated
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]Ownership of decisions [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]The Young Lambeth Coop (YLC)
[normal]The YLC is a completely independent, community owned organisation that exemplifies the council’s ambition to transfer control and decision-making to local communities. 
[normal]Over
[normal] 
[normal]800 community hours have already been committed to the YLC’s development and 1100 adults and 650 young people expressed interest in being involved in its development.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]YLC members will be responsible for a £6m budget deciding what play and youth services are provided across the borough. 
[normal]It is programmed to deliver the council 24% cashable savings and be 23% cheaper than the current commissioning model
[normal]. 
[normal]Furthermore it aims to commission an additional £3.8 million worth of services for young people over 5-years
[normal] of age
[normal], a significant proportion of which would not otherwise have been brought into the borough. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]To what extent is the government’s public service reform programme succeeding?
