[normal]What are the challenges of citizen centred approaches / and how can we ensure all citizen have influence?
[normal]Becoming facilitators and enablers[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Green Community Champions (GCC)
[normal]             
[normal]T
[normal]he Council made an open call to citizens to ask them if they would like to be green community champions and asked them to define what they wanted to do, supported by a single officer. There are now 500 champions working with over 60 groups and 5,000 residents on local environmental issues – from food growing to community energy projects. It has led to more innovation and community ownership than if the 
[normal]c
[normal]ouncil had 
[normal]defined the network 
[normal]at the outset. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Made in Lambeth
[normal]M
[normal]ade 
[normal]i
[normal]n 
[normal]L
[normal]ambeth
[normal] is a council facilitated hack-day type event 
[normal]where
[normal] volunteers work together over single weekends to address particular challenges within the borough.  Volunteers come from a range of backgrounds including graphic designers, artists, project managers and community organisers.  Projects they have worked on include designing a brand new website and branding for the Young Lambeth Coop, accelerating the approach to digital inclusion across the borough, re-launching Vauxhall City Farm and marketing affordable pay-day loan products from the London Mutual Credit Union.  The council facilitates these events through coordinating project briefs and providing a location and 
[normal]wifi
[normal].  However, the output is very much down to those who take part in the weekends.  This approach has enabled the council to harness the creativity of communities and helped create a more permissive council culture where creative changes 
[normal]designed by the community are put into practice.
[normal]Community 
[normal]Freshview
[normal]Community 
[normal]Freshview
[normal] is a community-led opportunity for residents to make a difference to their local area whether through brightening up a green space, giving a disused space a facelift or any other activity that improves the local environment.  The council provides nominal support such as plants and paint, expertise where needed
[normal],
[normal] and support in accessing additional volunteers.  In addition to sprucing up an area Community 
[normal]Freshview
[normal] has the benefit of bringing neighbours together and has been undertaken by more than 20 separate groups already.  This example has emphasised the value 
[normal]of 
[normal]providing a clear and simple 
[normal]offer
[normal] of council support for resident-led activity and highlighted how barriers to participati
[normal]on can be overcome through well 
[normal]publicised council support.
[normal]Evidencing what works[bold] and learning from early projects. [bold]Brixton Energy
[normal]Brixton Energy is a not-for-profit co-operative based in Lambeth creating cooperatively owned renewable energy projects whose financial revenues stay within the local community. It is the first social-housing based renewable energy company in the country with a vision to create a greener future for Brixton.  In doing so it is generating energy, increasing Brixton’s energy 
[normal]resilience and security, raising awareness about energy efficiency
[normal],
[normal] tackling fuel poverty
[normal],
[normal] and providing training and employment for local people.  It was established in cooperation with the council.  Since then five further roofs on the estate have been fitted with panels.
[normal]Conclusion [bold]These are challenging times; 
[normal]there is less funding and an increased d
[normal]emand for some public services.
[normal] 
[normal]T
[normal]here are risks but there are opp
[normal]ortunities too. The Lambeth approach is transformational bu
[normal]t we have achieved this through
[normal] a solid evidence base of support (through our Cooperative Council Commission)
[normal]; 
[normal] citizen engagement
[normal];
[normal] and early prototyping to develop our thinking and draw learning around issues of risk, organisational structure, accountability, behaviour change and capacity building. We have found that in order for the approach to work, the council must help mitigate risk
[normal],
[normal] but more importantly by building new relationships and putting the citizen in control we are saving money. Ultimately 
[normal]we believe that we will 
[normal]see a collaborative community
[normal] in Lambeth
[normal] where the council acts as a platform for
[normal] that
[normal] collaboration, providing the right spaces and infrastructure to make 
[normal]it
[normal] happen. By empowering local people in this way we can give them back the power to change their lives and help those around them, fostering stronger more resilient communities. 
[normal]October 2013
